# definitions

# sum of first integers: $\sum _{i=1}^{n} i$
$\sum _{i=1}^{n} i = \frac{1}{2} n (n+1)$

# sum of first squares $\sum _{i=1}^{n} i^2$
$\sum _{i=1}^{n} i^2 = \frac{1}{6} (n) (n+1) (2n+1)$


$$\sum\limits_{r=1}^{n} a^r = \frac{a-a^{n+1}}{1-a} $$

$$\sum\limits_{j=-k}^{n} f(j)= \sum\limits_{m=0} ^{n+k}f(m-k)$$

$$\sum_{k=1}^{n} = n$$ and $$\sum_{k=1}^{n} k = \frac{1}{2} n (n+1)$$


## distributive law
$\left( \sum _{R(i)} a_i \right) \left( \sum _{S(j)} b_j \right) = \sum _{R(j)} \sum _{S(j)} a_i b_j$

## change of variable
$$\sum _{R(i)} a_i = \sum _{R(j)} a_j = \sum _{R(p(j)} a_{p(j)}$$

$$\sum _{R(i)} a_i  = \sum _{R(p(j)} a_{p(j)}$$
There must be exactly one integer satisfying $p\left( j \right) = i$, so this is a permutation.

Usually this permuation function is $p(j) = c \pm j$

$$\sum _{1 \le j \le n} a_j = \sum _{1 \le j - 1 \le n} a_{j-1} & \text{ change of base formula }$$

$$ = \sum _{1 \le j - 1 \le n} a_{j-1}$$

The permuation function cannot be done for all infinite sums.

## interchanging order of summation
$$\sum _{R(i)} \sum _{S(j)} a_{ij} =  \sum _{S(j)} \sum _{R(i)} a_{ij}$$

~~~{.c .numberLines}
for (int i = 1; i < N; i++) {
	for (int j = 1; j < n; j++) {
		sum += a[i][j];
	}
}

/* Is the same as */

for (int j = 1; j < n; j++) {
	for (int i = j; i < N; i++) {
		sum += a[i][j];
	}
}
~~~

